<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence by John Linwood</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence by John Linwood</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I was the CTO of the BBC from April 2009 until 25 July 2013.  I chaired the DMI Steering Group, and I reported to the Executive Board at all material times during the project until October 2012.  In accordance with the project’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">structure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I was responsible for the delivery of the DMI technology.  A number of senior executives in BBC Vision (Television) who were members of the Steering Group were assigned responsibility for implementation of the technology and realisation of the benefits.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I have issued legal proceedings against the BBC and intimated contractual claims, and am still involved in an internal process with the BBC.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I do not think it appropriate to discuss my dispute with or claims against the BBC.  The purpose of this statement is to place before the PAC relevant facts which will aid the PAC in its understanding of the project and the events leading up to the decision by the BBC to write-off the full book value of the DMI assets.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">three major</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> parts or pillars of DMI, all of which fed into each other</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: Metadata Archive/Physical Stock and Loan, Production Tools, and Digital Archive.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It was necessarily a complex and innovative project, because the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> complex and unique requirements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Nothing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> existed then or exists today in the market</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">place which can meet all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the BBC’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> needs.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Throughout this statement I refer to BBC Vision (Television) and BBC North as the “business”.  My primary responsibility on the project was to ensure that we delivered the technology specified by the business.    The project was difficult and experienced delays.  However:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 67.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We delivered a substantial amount of the DMI technology;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The technology we delivered worked or could, with limited further testing, have worked.  It is either in use in the BBC today (e.g. the Metadata Archive) or capable of being used (e.g. Production Tools);</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 66.43pt; padding-left:5.57pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The business decided in October 2012 that its original vision for DMI had changed and it wanted to change direction so that they no longer wished to use Production </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Tools (which had been built at their request to standardise their production process);</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC has written off working software and hardware, some of which remains in use today;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 67.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC has allowed inaccurate statements to be made to the PAC to the effect that the “kit doesn’t work” and is “worth nothing”. </span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC has been fully aware for many months of the issues raised in this statement as I have raised them in correspondence and other communications with the BBC.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Project</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The DMI project was a ground-breaking and major business change project which relied on the delivery of technology to support the change in the way people were to work. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The project </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">was conceived</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by the business </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and started several years before I joined the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  The original goal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">was to move the BBC from tape-based production to computer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">based production of programmes and related archive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to deliver a single, pan-BBC solution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  This concept, which was articulated in the original business case,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> came from the business. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The objective was to reduce cost and make production more efficient.  The business case was revalidated by the business in 2010 when the project came back in-house.  Throughout my involvement in the project until October 2012 I believed that the business continued to subscribe to their DMI vision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.    </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We initially released the software we developed incrementally in the business, as part of “agile” development, but after the business objected to this approach we stopped.  Originally when the project came in-house from Siemens the initial plan was to use the code developed by Siemens but this proved unworkable and the timetable shifted.  The plan from as early as September 2010 was that the project would not go “live” in the BBC until early 2012, and this was known to the BBC Executive and to the BBC Trust.  We piloted the technology in the business from late 2011, as planned.  The project was subject to delays, and when the first major part of the project, the Metadata Archive, went live in June 2012, we were approximately six months behind schedule.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The primary reason for the delays was the significantly large number of changes requested by the business to the requirements which had been previously specified by them.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There were also some technology issues which caused delay, but all major technology issues had been addressed by the project by October 2012.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Production Tools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Production Tools would allow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> producers and editors to work on PCs instead of using editing suites and tape editing equipment to provide efficiency and cost savings.  It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> allow the content to be uploaded, looked at, marked up, strung together into a rough version, and then sent to the third party desktop edit package for final editing, with the option of capturing re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">levant metadata at every point.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">required a change in the way people did their jobs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roduction users would have to standardise their production processes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to achieve the full benefits envisaged.  I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t was a major business change.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Throughout the project it was intended that Production Tools would be used by all of Vision and North Production except for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">News and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sport.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DMI Production Tools was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a desktop editing function.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Production Tools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was never going to provide the whole production solution but was going to provide a layer additional to the third party desktop edit software packages available then and now.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Metadata Archive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> /</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Physical Stock and Loan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The second part of DMI was to deliver a search capability to find content (both tape and, ultimately, digital) in the archive.  This was called the “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Metadata Archive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”.  It contains all the information about a programme, such as who is in it, when it was first broadcast, who owns the rights, etc.  It is a searchable archive of information.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The system to allow searching of that content so that production users could order it from the archive was also to be an online self-service system.  On completion of the whole project this was intended ultimately to allow direct downloading by production users of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">digital </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">content </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">loaded via Production Tools.  It would also be a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">self-service on-line ordering process for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the historic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">physical media, such as tapes or films, from the BBC’s Archive.  This part of the project was called “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Physical Stock and Loan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”.  Previously this was done by filling out a form</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> making a telephone call to Information and Archive.  The objective was to move use of the system from Information and Archive to the Production users themselves, and cut out the midd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e-man.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  This would lead to head-count reduction and cost-savings.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Digital Archive</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The DMI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Digital Archive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was designed to digitise the content produced on Production Tools.  It would</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> support the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">online </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">warehousing of video and audio content on central computer systems and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">accessible from anywhere in the BBC.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ontent produced on the Production Tools system would be automatically fed or ingested into the repository. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t was always envisaged that the Digital Archive was the lowest priority on the DMI project, and Finance Committee sanctioned this approach on 10 February 2012.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Digital archive was not a priority because until Production Tools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was operational there would be no content on it (because DMI architecture relied on content being created on Production Tools to flow through to the Digital</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Archive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Once Production Tools was operational all digitised content would have been automatically digitised and warehoused in the Digital Archive.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I have read press reports critical of the DMI project and the lack of delivery of a digital archive, relating to the access producers had to archive material of Margaret Thatcher on her death.  The DMI project was never intended to address that class of content.    The digitisation of the BBC historic archive was out of scope of the DMI project.  At</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the conclusion of the DMI project the BBC would still have had significant number of tapes, film, etc. produced prior to DMI (over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one million</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> items)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Media Infrastructure</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">derlying these core components was a technology platform to connect the various parts of the system allowing metadata and content to move through the system and to interface DMI to dozens of existing BBC systems that sit around the production process.  This is called “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Media Infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Music Reporting</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The project was also intended to deliver rights management for the content and to provide reporting on the use of the content (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Music Reporting and Video Reporting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">).  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">B:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What was delivered by October 2012</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Metadata Archive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> / Physical Stock and Loan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> went live in June 2012 and remains in use by thousands of users in the BBC today.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Production Tools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was delivered and tested and was ready to go live in October 2012.  During the pilot phase both long-form and short-form content was produced successfully and broadcast by the BBC and the software was functionally complete by October 2012.  Despite this, in October 2012, the business decided it no longer wished to use Production Tools.  The reasons given by the business to the Executive Board in May 2013 was that there had been a change in business direction and the original vision of DMI no longer being valid.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The code for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Digital Archive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">had been written and we were awaiting the launch of Production Tools before completing the Digital Archive.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Some testing was done </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">but this was stopped when the business decided not to use Production Tools.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The entire </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">edia </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nfrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (hardware and networks) ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> been bought and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in place.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Media Infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">was tested and is in use for and supports the Metadata Archive and the Media Infrastructure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that supports media movement and storage for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Production </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Tools has been tested for Production Tools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not been tested for Digital Archive as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that was not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> deployed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Music Reporting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> went live in early 2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and remains live and in use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">C:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Scrapping of Production Tools</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All major technical issues which were identified during the piloting phase of Production Tools were addressed.  By 4 October 2012, s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ignificant performance and functional testing had been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">successfully completed and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the key requirements specified by the business had been met.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We were in final technical testing, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Production Tools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was ready to go live.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Over the early months of 2012 it had become evident that the business was not speaking with one voice in relation to its requirements for Production Tools and that there was no senior owner on the business side who would take responsibility for implementation of the technology.  I raised these concerns at the highest level in the BBC and the Executive with whom I spoke had some success in persuading BBC Vision to appoint a senior executive from Vision to the Steering Group.  However after the former Director-General and the Chief Operating Officer departed in late summer/early autumn 2012 a change in direction by the business became apparent for the first time.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">October 2012 the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Steering Group documents record that Production Tools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technology was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">functionally complete</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Production confirm that Production Tools were viable and candidate productions were identified</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Our discussions with Production representatives in London, Salford and Bristol suggest that with PT12</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">we have sufficient functionality for a viable production workflow and to derive some efficiency benefits for Vision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">No dissent over this report was expressed at that meeting.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, in spite of this, the business announced at the Steering Group on 4 October 2012 that it was not going to use Production Tools because the business no longer wanted a standardised production process.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here were different requirements in different departments and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">they said </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it didn’t make sense any more to have a single</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, standardised,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> product</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion process across the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Their vision, upon which the whole project had been predicated, had changed.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The minutes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of the Steering Group </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">record that the business requested to suspend Production Tools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> after completion of the next release</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> due to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">unclear business direction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This decision would have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> significant implications for the whole of the DMI project.  By way of analogy this change was equivalent to removing the first half of a production line in a factory and still expecting the factory to deliver the original products.  It affected the way the content and metadata would have to be loaded into the Digital Archive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  It meant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> we would have to interface with different systems</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  It</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> affected file based delivery which was dependent on Production Tools, it affected how we would store the content and capture metadata.  The design and architecture of the Digital Archive depended heavily on processes and functionality that was delivered in Production Tools.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">questioned the decision.  I said that we were hearing from the business that different production teams were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">actively testing P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roduction Tools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and did want it and would use it.   I also pointed out that if the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> business decided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not to use </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Production Tools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">then there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be significant re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">architect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing work to be done </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to the rest of the technology on the project.  I was told expressly and in writing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in an email dated 15 October 2012 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Finish the current plan of work on PT13, then stop.  That’s the clear view of the business</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.”   </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At the DMI Steering Group on 19 October</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the representative </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from corporate finance (who reported to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the CFO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) flagged up the need to be aware of the costs and implications to the BBC of stopping then restarting Production Tools Development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and this was recorded in the minutes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.    </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The DMI Steering Group minutes from 19 October 2012 state that the business requested to suspend Production Tools “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">due to unclear business requirements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Since the decision not to use Production Tools was taken the BBC has referred in many documents to the reasons for this decision being “change of vision”, “changed requirements”, “changing environment”, “reformulation of the fundamental vision”, the “significant change in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the business context</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and the fact that Production Tools and the Digital Archive/Media Infrastructure work should be suspended until the business g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ve a clear direction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Production Tools is currently mothballed.  The BBC’s vision for the technology solution it wants has now changed.  I believe that the DMI project would have been delivered and the benefits realised by now if the business had wanted to take Production Tools live. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">D. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Accenture Report</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Following the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scrapping</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by the BBC of Production Tools, Accenture </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">asked to review </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Metadata Archive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which was already live,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the light of the BBC’s changed vision.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Accenture spent five weeks in January and February </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reviewing  the Metadata Archive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from the perspective of what could be used in the light of the new vision, i.e. how its architecture, originally envisaged as part of the wider DMI project, could work for the new or changed vision of the BBC.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They found that the architecture of the Metadata Archive was complex for the changed vision, which was a much simpler vision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> than the integrated DMI vision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  In spite of this, Accenture recommended </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“there is enough potential value in DMI to move ahead with plans to build on it”.  The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recommended </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">keeping the metadata archive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and building on it.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  They said it would cost £25 million to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> start to rebuild the technology from scratch to get to the same position.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The metadata archive remains in use.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I believe in excess of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">000 users of this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the BBC.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The scope of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Accenture </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">review entirely excluded Production Tools because </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the BBC had “deprioritised” Production Tools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> so there has been no independent review of this aspect of the technology.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Accenture did not review the code for the Digital Archive.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Accenture made no finding of any technology failure.  Accenture expressed no view about the viability of Production Tools or the Digital Archive.  To the best of my knowledge and belief, and based on the reporting to me by the Project Team throughout the project, the DMI technology which we built works.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC stated at the Public Accounts Committee hearing on 10 June 2013 that Accenture found in its review that “the kit doesn’t work” and is “worth nothing”.  Accenture did not find that “the kit did not work” nor did they find that it was “worth nothing”.    </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The PwC Report</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PwC did </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not review “the programme delivery or any element of the technology delivery, business change activities, DMI technical solution, or the decision to write down the asset”.  PwC found that there was “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">no single event or issue that was the root cause of DMI failing to deliver its anticipated benefits</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Guardian newspaper appears to have had access to a draft of the PwC report and in an article dated 17 December 2013 indicated that the PwC report was critical of impact that the speed the write-down had on the value of the remaining DMI assets.  Any such criticisms appear to have been excised from the published version of the report.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Write-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">down</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Finance Committee on 29 April 2013 was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">asked </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">give its approval to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">permanently close down Production Tools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Preparatory documents authored by the business for the Finance Committee indicated that the BBC no longer wanted or needed a single set of production tools that were common across TV production.  Commodity tools were available and “would enable sensible flexibility in production bases”.  What was required was “common standards not common tools,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> interoperability, not integration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The paper before the committee stated: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Several years ago it was imagined that the journey to end-to-end digital was best achieved through the creation of an enterprise solution, with standardised production tools and processes, and an ability to associate all business and archive systems with production assets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">…… such</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> a vision is no longer seen as appropriate either from a creative or from a business point of view.  The most appropriate focus for E2E Digital has now shifted.  It sits firmly around the creation of an effective central digital archive which is able to interface with separate key business systems and with systems for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the distribution of content to audiences, across a variety of platforms.  By focusing on the digital archive, and delivery in and out of it, we are better able to increase our agility right across our business – from commissioning to distribution – in response to the changing behaviours and demands of audiences</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I attended </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Finance Committee meeting on 29 April 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  It was the only occasion on which I met the new Director General.  I raised objections to the proposed level of write-down on the project at the meeting (which at that stage had grown </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from £24M </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to £40M)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">expressing the view that the proposed level of write-down was too high because the technology work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and either </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> being or could be used.  The Director General stated at the meeting that he wanted to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">maximise the write-down</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On 29 April 2013 the Finance Committee took a decision to approve a recommendation by the End to End Steering Group that they “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Approve that the original vision of DMI for a singled, integrated digital Production Toolset is no longer valid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” and made a number of related findings.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">minutes of the meeting state that “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The DG noted that in respect of the accounting write off we should seek to make one write down only and therefore it should be the maximum and not the minimum</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The papers to the Executive Board in May 2013 reflect the change in direction and the Board was made aware of the Finance Committee’s decision of 29 April that “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the original vision of DMI for a single integrated digital production toolset is no longer valid and as such DMI Production Tools should be permanently stopped and any assets created or bought for this purpose should be redeployed where possible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”, and that “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the revised direction for E2E Digital Production together with the findings of the independent technical review by Accenture will necessitate a write-down of assets held by the BBC of between £24.4 million and £40.2 million</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Executive Board wrote off the full value of the DMI project, some £53 million, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on 13 May 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  In the light of what had been delivered, the technology which was in use and ready to be used, my view was and remains that the scale of the write-down was unjustified.  The reason for the write-down was because the BBC did not wish to take live one pillar of the technology it had commissioned, and which we had delivered, due to its change of vision and direction.    </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I raised my concerns with the BBC about the accuracy of the BBC’s statements made on 10 June 2013 to the Public Accounts Committee and restated my concerns about the unjustified write-down in a letter to the BBC dated 24 June 2013.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I believe the content of this statement to be true.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">23 January 2014</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>